<activity xml:id="act-LimitsOfPolynomials">
    <title>Limits of Polynomial Functions</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We're going to use a combination of properties from <xref ref="thm-CombinationsOfLimits"/> and <xref ref="thm-LimitsOfTwoFunctions"/> to think a bit more deeply about polynomial functions. Let's consider a polynomial function:
                <me>
                    f(x) =  2x^4-4x^3+\frac{x}{2}-5
                </me>
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                We're going to evaluate the limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} f(x)</m>. First, use the properties from <xref ref="thm-CombinationsOfLimits"/> to rewrite this limit as 4 different limits added or subtracted together.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <me>\lim_{x\to 1} (2x^4) - \lim_{x\to 1} (4x^3) + \lim_{x\to 1}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right) - \lim_{x\to 1} 5</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now, for each of these limits, rewrite them as products of things until you have only limits of constants and identity functions, as in <xref ref="thm-LimitsOfTwoFunctions"/>. Evaluate your limits.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <me>2\left(\lim_{x\to 1} x\right)^4 - 4\left(\lim_{x\to 1} x\right)^3 + \frac{1}{2}\left(\lim_{x\to 1}x\right) - \lim_{x\to 1} 5</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Based on the definition of a limit (<xref ref="def-Limit"/>), we normally say that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} f(x)</m> is not dependent on the value of <m>f(1)</m>. Why do we say this?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Compare the values of <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} f(x)</m> and <m>f(1)</m>. Why do these values feel connected?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Come up with a new polynomial function: some combination of coefficients with <m>x</m>'s raised to natural number exponents. Call your new polynomial function <m>g(x)</m>. Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to -1} g(x)</m> and compare the value to <m>g(-1)</m>. Explain why these values are the same.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain why, for any polynomial function <m>p(x)</m>, the limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a}p(x)</m> is the same value as <m>p(a)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
</activity>